article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw and Tamika Whitmore scored 17 points apiece to lead the host Los Angeles Sparks to an 83-64 rout of the Houston Comets on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Holdsclaw, Whitmore score 17 each; Teasley reaches 1,000
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Struggling with their shooting all season,
Los Angeles Sparks coach Henry Bibby believes his team has turned
it around with the the best shooting performance in franchise
history.

Chamique Holdsclaw and Tamika Whitmore scored 17 points apiece
and the Sparks shot a team-record 65.5 percent in an 83-64 rout of
the Houston Comets on Wednesday night.

"The train is headed in the right direction," Bibby said. "We
haven't shot the ball well up until the last couple of games. We're
spending maybe 25 to 30 minutes in practice just on shooting."

Lisa Leslie added 14 points for Los Angeles (5-4) before fouling
out.

Michelle Snow and Sancho Lyttle each scored 13 points for the
Comets (4-5), losers of four straight after a 4-1 start.

"I think the Sparks were excellent," Houston coach Van
Chancellor said. "If they play like that, everybody in this league
is going to be in trouble -- everybody."

Leslie and Nikki Teasley scored six points apiece as the Sparks
took a 16-8 lead in the first 3:45, en route to building a 13-point
lead. Teasley's 3-point basket 2:10 into the game gave her 1,000
career points.

Houston narrowed its deficit to 37-28 on Snow's four-point play
with 4:44 left in the first half. But the Comets failed to score
the rest of the half as the Sparks built a 46-28 lead.

Los Angeles extended the margin to 23 points with 13:20 to play,
as the Sparks made eight of their first 11 shots in the second half
and the Comets missed 10 of their first 13.
